posts.name: Brody Anderson
posts.cooked:
I’m working on a Blockly-to-Java app aimed at helping students and rookie programmers transition into writing FRC code more easily, along with giving an easy route for Java mockups. To make the tool as helpful as possible, I’m trying to get the most useful methods in first, so I’d love your input:

What Java libraries or classes do you use the most in your robot code? (Which imports do you find yourself using most?)

What would be most helpful for teaching students?

What would you have wanted included if you were just starting out?

Thank you in advance for the feedback!

posts.name: Hao Huang
posts.cooked: REVLib and Phoenix are crucial for me

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
Our robot code has the usual suspects for the classes - WPILib, RevLib, Phoenix, LimeLight, PathPlanner.

Typically, programmers use the import statement instead of writing out the class path in front of each method. You could search github for FRC teams’ repositories.

posts.name: Brody Anderson
posts.cooked: Our team uses imports as well, I was mainly looking for which imports should have highest priority in development. Thank you for mentioning looking at other teams repos, that’ll probably work best
The most popular will be WPIlib, Revlib, and phoenix Lib.

posts.name: Nolan Barker
posts.cooked: PhotonVision is another widely popular library I haven’t seen mentioned yet.

posts.name: Eren
posts.cooked: Not specifically FRC Related, but we use Lombok in some of our projects. It’s pretty convenient. For example, it has annotations for classes that automatically generate getter and setter methods.

posts.name: Brody Anderson
posts.cooked: Thank you, my current issue is there is only one person adding blocks in its current state, so REVLib, Phoenix, and so on are probably too big for me to go through before the next season starts once you take in to account WPILib as well. What interfaces within these do you use the most?

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked:
You can do the setter and getter methods by using a record, if you’re programming in Java.

The above is incorrect, records only generate getter methods, not setter methods as well.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: I know next to nothing about this, but do you think it would be possible to add an auto generator from code for the blocks? This might speed things up, and let dev time be spent on more productive things than rote copying.
I am working on a few new ones that may integrate nicely in the future that you should look out for. The planned release date is Oct 2nd

posts.name: Hao Huang
posts.cooked:
Consider checking out the SparkBase class from REVLib. It’d be great to have most of the getters and setters implemented

For Phoenix 6, check out the TalonFX motor class; and for Phoenix 5, it’d be cool to have support for TalonSRX controllers

Anyway, it would be super helpful to have basic support for controllers and motors so we can at least get them running!!!

ps. i replied to the wrong thing…

posts.name: Brody Anderson
posts.cooked: It may be possible to make a more efficient code generator, my current method is inputting sample block formats/code generation and the methods/constructors of the api I’m copying down into deepseek, and then modifying a little further from there. The main problem with an auto generator is that the most efficient block creator isn’t always the most beginner friendly or space efficient (ie; having a drop down for controller buttons instead of one block for every one, or something that has multiple constructors that could all be put into one block)
